<br>
The gavel hit the desk with enough force to knock over the Judicar's Quill, and the second (*Bang*) crushed the frail feather into the wood. <br>
<br>
Ignorant of the ruined writing impliment, the human sneered at the courtroom, commanding silence from the mob that had recently grown unruly. Bargin Truthblade still had a lot of cases to get through today, and he was not going to let this one Bard ruin his whole day. <br>
<br>
&quot;Guards, have the elf gagged&quot;<br>
<br>
Bargin smiled as the bard's eyes grew large, and he raised a finger to protest but was quickly subdued. A flurry of activity later and the red headed elf was lifted to his feet, his nose bleeding down into the rag that had been tied around his mouth.<br>
<br>
All too often had a bard come in and try to sway the opinions of those in the court with their magics, and Bargin tired of it easily. Fiddling with the ring that granted him a certain resistance to such charms, he watched the jury as their looks of empathy for the bard returned to the looks of contempt he had chosen these jurors for. <br>
<br>
Eyes swinging back towards the proceedings, he studied the two sides. The three defendants, the elf, an albino dwarf, and a waif human girl, stood behind one podium, while the prosecutor, a sharply dressed militia guard, stood behind the other. A smug grin played about the prosecutor's face, as he also glanced over at the defendant's table. Moving from behind his podium, he approached the jury.<br>
<br>
&quot;As I was saying, before I was interrupted by such rude and callious remarks, was that on the day in question the defendants did willingly and with prior malace attack and kill our local hero, the Gallant Sir Lucan!&quot; With this the lawyer pointed towards the witness stand, to a well dressed militia officer. The man sat smug, cleaning some dirt that had appeared under his fingernail. <br>
<br>
The jury gasped at this accusation, despite having heard and gasped at it three times before. Kuladen rolled his eyes, and strugged against the handcuffs that bound his hands behind his back. <br>
<br>
Bargin ignored the defendants for a moment, and studied the jurors. All on the payroll of the Militia, he had personally worked with several before, and found them to be fair and impartial, as long as they sided with the Freeport Militia. <br>
<br>
A sound, though, broke his concentration, and he turned his head quickly to see the bard's hands free, pulling the gag from his mouth. Quickly grabbing up a parchment, he rolled it into a tube and started to blow through it. <br>
<br>
Lights began playing off the three defendants as the waif girl grabbed both the elf and the dwarf, drawing the three close together. The guards lept at the three, only to grab empty air. With a slight WOOOSH sound the three disappeared, only to reappear in three different locations. <br>
<br>
The elf appeared inside the jury box, landing on a sweet old man and breaking the chair beneath the two. The albino dwarf appeared a mere two feet from his previous location, and was quickly subdued. The girl, however, vanished from sight, and after a quick search was nowhere to be found. <br>
<br>
(*BANG*) <br>
<br>
&quot;ORDER IN THIS COURTROOM. Guards, please bring the two defendents into order with whatever force is necessary&quot;<br>
<br>
Several action packed minutes later the Elf and Dwarf were standing behind the defendent table again, bloodied, and hunched over from all the chains about them. <br>
<br>
Bargin smiled as he heard the dwarf comment to the elf 'Ye could have picked a better song than that, dunderhead.'<br>
<br>
The elf remained silent, perhaps due to the two gags and sword at the base of his neck.<br>
<br>
